Moodtracker and Emotional State Reports¶

This Notebook covers two of the requested reports:

  • A report on the retention and use of the moodtracker feature
  • A report on the employee emotional state and evolution per industry

Since the information necessary for both reports is shared, it was decided that both would share the same notebook, so that they can share the same functions, variables and transformations.

# Utility functions

# These could've been lambda functions, but the function name is used as the column name, so it's handier this way
def male_count(series:pd.Series):
    return sum(series == 'male')

def female_count(series:pd.Series):
    return sum(series == 'female')

def male_female_ratio(series:pd.Series):
    return sum(series == 'male')/sum(series == 'female')

def unknown_count(series:pd.Series):
    return sum(series == 'unknown')

def get_mode(series:pd.Series, last=True):
    """
    This function returns the mode of a series.
    If there is no clear mode value it takes either the first or last value
    """
    ind = 1 if last else 0
    mode = series.mode()
    if mode.shape[0] > 1:
        return mode[ind]
    else:
        return mode[0]
    
def diff_time(series:pd.Series):
    """
    Compute the time difference between consecutive timestamps in a series
    """
    datetime_series = pd.Series(pd.to_datetime(series))
    sorted_series = datetime_series.sort_values()
    return list(sorted_series.diff())

# Plotting functions
def mood_evolution(df, subset_text='All population'):
    """
    Plot a stacked barplot of the mood evolution of a given dataframe
    """
    mood_count_date = df.groupby(["trackedat_date", "mood"])["userid"].count().reset_index()

    # Subset data per mood type
    subset_list = []
    for mood_v in mood_count_date["mood"].unique():
        subset_list.append(mood_count_date.query("mood == @mood_v")[["trackedat_date","userid", "mood"]])

    # Plot
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30,10))
    ax_list=[]
    for i, s in enumerate(subset_list):
        if i == 0:
            p = plt.bar(x='trackedat_date', height = "userid",
                   data=s)
            ax_list.append(p[0])
            leg_list=[s["mood"].unique()[0]]
        else:
            p = plt.bar(x='trackedat_date', height = "userid",
                   data=s, bottom = subset_list[i-1]["userid"])
            ax_list.append(p[0])
            leg_list=leg_list+[s["mood"].unique()[0]]

    plt.title("Mood evolution" + f" ({subset_text})")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Reported cases")
    plt.tick_params('x',labelrotation=70)
    plt.legend(ax_list, leg_list)

    plt.show()
    
    
def mood_comparison(df, mood1, mood2):
    q_string = f"mood == '{mood1}' or mood == '{mood2}'"
    ex_mood = df.query(q_string).groupby(["trackedat_date", "mood"])["userid"].count().reset_index().copy()
    chart=sns.catplot(x = 'trackedat_date', y =  'userid',
               hue='mood', data=ex_mood, kind = 'bar', height = 6, aspect=4, legend=False)

    chart_l = sns.lineplot(x = 'trackedat_date', y =  'userid',data=ex_mood, 
                           hue = 'mood', dashes =True, markers=True, legend=False)

    plt.setp(chart_l.lines, alpha=.3)

    chart.set(xlabel = 'Date',
             ylabel='Number of users',
             title='Number of users super-happy or angry per day')

    plt.legend(loc='best')

    plt.xticks(rotation = 70)
    plt.show()

# Query to fetch a simple user table with company and industry names
pop_q = f'''
-- Get users and their company and industry
select distinct u.id as userid,
                u.name as username,
                u.age as userage,
                cm.name as companyname,
                i.name as industryname
from users u 
left join companies cm
on(cast(u.companyid as text) = cm.id )
left join industries i 
on(i.id = cast(u.industryid as text) )
;
'''

pop_df = pd.read_sql_query(pop_q, engine)
pop_df.head()

Straight away, one thing we can do to augment our data is to try to guess what is the gender of the user based on their name. We can infer that using a package such as https://pypi.org/project/gender-guesser/.

In [4]:
# Create a detector object
genderDetector = gender.Detector()

# We guess the the genders and then check what we got
pop_df['genderguess'] = pop_df.username.apply(lambda x: genderDetector.get_gender(x))

print(f"Out of {pop_df['userid'].nunique()} users, this was the proportion of genders guessed:")
display(pop_df['genderguess'].value_counts())

Out of 2000 users, this was the proportion of genders guessed:

female           883
male             831
unknown          147
mostly_male       62
mostly_female     51
andy              26
dtype: int64

With this we were able to guess around 86% as definitively either male of female. Some remarks:

  • The mostly_male and mostly_female labels represent 3.1% and 2.6% of the population so we are going to join them with the male and female labels for simplicity.
  • The andy label represents names that can be either male or female. This label represents 1.3% of our population. Since this is such a low value we are going to keep it as it's own thing instead of drilling down further.
  • The unknow label represents names that the detector was unable to guess as either gender. They are 7.35% of our population, so it's also a small subset. The total number of distinct names is 116. Since the gender is just a guess, there is no point in trying to fit the these into either of the male or female labels.

                    "mostly_female": 'female',

# Save categories as factor to save memory
pop_df["genderguess"]=pop_df["genderguess"].astype('category')

In the above table we can see that the groups we get by splitting the users per company and industry are very similar when it comes to age and gender.

  • The min age registered for each group is 18 years for all groups.
  • The max age is either 40 or 41, with one exception (39)
  • The median age is always between 24 and 29 years old, while the mean is within the interval (26; 29) years old.
  • When it comes to guessedgender the ratio between male and female is also very similar among the different groups, and usually close to 1.

In [12]:
# Let's check how many days each user has on the moodtracker feature as well as the time interval between consecutive logs
user_engagement_df = moodtracker_df.groupby("userid").agg({"trackedat_date":"nunique",
                                     "trackedat": diff_time}).reset_index()

user_engagement_df.rename(columns = {"trackedat_date": "number_of_days",
                                    "trackedat" : 'time_between_logs'}, inplace=True)

# We merge all the time differences in a single series so we can compute summary statistics over all the population
time_between_consecutive_logs = pd.Series(user_engagement_df.time_between_logs.sum())

# The first entry for each user is always NaT, so we can remove that
time_between_consecutive_logs.dropna(inplace=True)

# We convert the time difference to minutes for readability
time_between_consecutive_logs_m = time_between_consecutive_logs.apply(lambda x: x.seconds/60)

# Let's plot both distributions
f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20,5))

sns.boxplot(x=user_engagement_df.number_of_days, ax=ax1)
ax1.set_xlabel("Number of days")
ax1.set_title("Usage of the moodtracker per user")

sns.boxplot(x=time_between_consecutive_logs_m/60, ax=ax2)
ax2.set_xlabel("Hours")
ax2.set_title("Time between consecutive logs")

plt.show()

The plots above shows for how long users used the moodtracker feature as well as how frequently they did it.

From the left plot we can see that most of the users used the moodtracker up to 19 to 27 days, with the median at 24 days and the mean close to 23 days. The 27 days limit is a curious one, since it lines up with the day where the big drop in moodtracker logs is registered (2020-01-28).

The right plot shows the time passed in hours between a user's consecutive logs. Here we can already see that there might be an issue on our table, since we have a minimum value of 0 hours, meaning that there are users with more than one log in the same instant of time. This is something we will get back to later.

We can observe with this plot that 50% of the users waits between 2 to 14 hours before returning to use the moodtracker. We can see how this data is affected by the drop in users towards the end of the month by looking at the mean (~8 hours) vs the median (~5 hours). Since the median is more resistent to outlier values, it's expected that if the sudden drops at the end of the month hadn't happened, then these values would be closer, meaning that on average our users wait around 5 hours before using the moodtracker feature again.

First & Last Seen ¶

Another interesting measure we can take is the number of users first seen on a given day and the number of last seen. This can also show us the first and last mood logged per user.

In [13]:
# First seen + Last seen on
first_seen = moodtracker_df.sort_values(["userid", "trackedat"]).drop_duplicates("userid", keep='first')
last_seen = moodtracker_df.sort_values(["userid", "trackedat"]).drop_duplicates("userid", keep='last')

# Plot both curves
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sns.lineplot(x = 'index', 
             y = 0,
             data=pd.DataFrame(first_seen.trackedat_date.value_counts()[1:]).reset_index()
            )

sns.lineplot(x = 'index', 
             y = 0,
             data=pd.DataFrame(last_seen.trackedat_date.value_counts()[1:]).reset_index()
            )

plt.title("First seen vs Last seen")
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of users')
plt.tick_params('x',labelrotation=70)

plt.legend(('First Seen', 'Last Seen'))
plt.show()

To make the plot above, the first and last day of the month were excluded, since we don't have visibility into the periods before and after this month, so we can't make any statement about the number of new/leaving users on those days. This is also relevant when discussing the "Last Seen" curve, since we don't know if users that may have "left" the moodtracker actually used it again on the following month.

Looking at the "First Seen" curve, we see that the amount of new users during the month decreased almost exponentially and from 2020-01-11 forwards, no new user was registered.

Regarding the "Last Seen" curve, we can see that up until 2020-01-23, there were no users stopping the usage of the moodtracker. This value only starts to increase significantly around 2020-01-26. We can see a local maxima at 2020-01-27 and the maximum value at 2020-01-29. These are the days that precede the big drops in the number of moodtracker logs.

In the plots above the y axis (Number of users) is share between both plots, to better compare the number of users. Also, just like before, the first and last day of the month were excluded.

We can see on the left-side plot, that most users first show up with a "angry" or "super-happy" mood, but as time goes on, there is more balance on the amount of each mood registered. On the right-side we can see an almost mirror progression, as the number of users "leaving" increases, so does the difference between the mood categories.

There are a total of 99996 logs.
The probability of a user using the tracker 5 or more times is 6.14%

Like shown in the plot above, usually the vast majority of users tend to use the moodtracker between 1 to 3 times per day (this group represent around 68% of the registers in the table). We also see that there is a very low probability of a user using the moodtracker 5 or more times in the same day.

This plot raises 2 questions though:

  • The total of logs computed from the plot is 99996 logs instead of the original 100000. What happened to the missing 4?
  • This plot does not show the amount of different moods logged throughout the day. What if a user logs more than 1 mood per day?

There are a total of 82994 logs.
The probability of a user registering 3 or more distinct moods is 20.65%

Similar to what've seen before, most of the users log 1 or 2 different kinds of mood in a given day. We can see that only 1 in 4 people register 3 or more distinct mood statuses in a day. It's important to make this distinction, since it will be crucial in how we go about analysing the mood of the users over time.

Like before, we have inconsistent number of logs, 82994 vs 100000. We aggregated our data by userid and date. If in the same day, the same user logged the same mood more than once, we are only counting it once (hence the importance of being explicit about distinct mood values).

Now that we have some insights regarding the use of the moodtracker, we can start to think about how to connect the information on moodtracker_df with the one of the population.

Emotional State Analysis ¶

Our target variable is mood. This is a categorical variable, meaning that we can't simply compute it's average value for each day, since all we have are strings.

  • Since we have some insight on the moodtracker data, we can transform our table to make our life easier while still using the data correctly. Here's what we know:
    • Most users don't use the moodtracker feature more than 2~3 times per day.
    • 80% of the users log either 1 or 2 distinct moods in a day.
    • A user can log the same mood more than once in a day.
  • With these informations in mind, we're going to edit our moodtracker table so that we only have 1 mood value per user per day. The steps to do this are:
    • Take the most frequent mood for each user, each day.
    • If there is no clear value that is more frequent than the others, take the last one registered.
  • This analysis will be biased towards the mood of people at the end of the day.
In [19]:
# Create a copy of the original dataframe for transformation
c_moodtracker_df = moodtracker_df.copy()

# We sort the dataframe here to be easier to take the last value if no mode exists
c_moodtracker_df.sort_values(["userid", "trackedat"], inplace=True)

# Aggregate with the custom get_mode function
c_moodtracker_df = c_moodtracker_df.groupby(["userid", "trackedat_date"]).agg({"mood" : get_mode}).reset_index()

General Population ¶

In [20]:
# Plot mood evolution for entire population
mood_evolution(c_moodtracker_df)

From the plot above we can see the extreme moods ('super-happy' and 'angry') are the most common moods reported.

'Sad' and 'Ok' mood follow, not being represented every day, but with significant expression in some cases. It seems like whenever there is an increase in the amount of users registering either 'angry' or 'super-happy' moods is at the cost of these moods, since they are reduced and sometimes even supressed fairly regularly.

Curiously the 'happy' mood is very rare, even more than the unknow (in the legend colored blue).

Since 'super-happy' and 'angry' dwarf the remaining mood statuses, we're going to drill down further in those.

In [21]:
# Plot extreme moods comparison
mood_comparison(c_moodtracker_df, 'angry', 'super-happy')

We can see that the number of users that keep either mood status from one day to another is stable. An increase in either mood does not reflect in a decrease in the opposite one, as noted previously. Like mentioned before, the drop in the final days of the month are proportional for these moods.

Now that we've seen the picture for the total population, we can drill down on different subsets. For that we will finally integrate the pop_df table. We are going to look into the following subsets:

  • All users that work in each industry
  • All users that work in each company
  • All users of a given (guessed) gender - only considering male or female here
  • All users of a given age range - 3 groups: <= 21 years old | > 21 & < 32 years old | >= 32 years old (these groups were decided based on the quantiles of the age of the total users)

The results will be discussed at the end.

Note: Since the '' (unknown) mood does not add a lot of information when we reduce our population size, so for these subset analysis we are going to discard those entries.

In [22]:
# We're going to join our transformed moodtracker table with pop_df
# but first we remove all unknown moods
s_moodtracker_df = c_moodtracker_df.query("mood !=''").copy()

In this section we can see that:

  • Marketing:
    • Marketing shows more variability than the overall population, especially in the beginning and toward the middle of the month.
    • The evolution of the "extreme" moods is a more sharp version of what's observed for the general population.
  • Finance:
    • The first 5 days for this industry are some of the ones with more diversity. On the 3rd, 4th and 5th of January either the "Ok" or "Sad" moods are more significant than "Angry"
    • This industry is the one where "Angry" and "Super-happy" have the closest values.
  • Sales:
    • Along with Marketing, here we see almost all the moods representend almost everyday.
    • Regarding the "extreme" moods, this groups shows the biggest fluctuations, however the gap between both moods widens after they've been registered in almost equal proportion.
  • Tech:
    • Biggest group, along with Marketing, is very similar to the overall evolution.
    • Unlike Marketing, the "extreme" mood plot is not similar to the overall plot, with some spikes that are not as visible in the overall plot.

On the age groups, we can see that the group of users under 21 years old show more diversity in the moods reported each day.

The mood "happy" has almost no expression in the second group (the largest group registered). This group has the least recorded diversity per day and of the three groups, is the one where the "sad" mood is more prevalent. This is also the largest group.

The last group stands a bit between the previous ones, showing more variability and diversity than the second group but less than the first. When it comes to the "extreme" mood plot, the biggest gap between "angry" and "super-happy" users is registeres here, in the second half of the month.
